he books, serial works, magazines, and newspapers published between 1900 and the outbreak of World War II to show that practicing scientists were very active in writing about their work for a general readership. Science for All argues that the social environment of early twentieth-century Britain created a substantial market for science books and magazines aimed at those who had benefited from better secondary education but could not access higher learning. Scientists found it easy and profitable to write for this audience, Bowler reveals, and because their work was seen as educational, they faced no hostility from their peers. But when admission to colleges and universities became more accessible in the 1960s, this market diminished and professional scientists began to lose interest in writing at the nonspecialist level. Eagerly anticipated by scholars of scientific engagement throughout the ages, Science for All sheds light on our own era and the continuing tension between science and public understanding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCommunication in sciencezGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aScience newszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ascience, history, britain, publishing, education, college, dissemination, magazines, nonfiction, information production, discovery, innovation, practical mechanics, evolution, astronomy, space, communication, technology, victorian, 20th century, war, interwar, military, advancements, progress, england, empire, colonialism, biology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226068664423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226068664/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press 